[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926914&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926914&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

In the old days of host tables, if I knew any part (say gorn) of a dimly-
and imperfectly remembered hostname, I could do "fgrep gorn /etc/hosts"
(excuse the UNIX-centricity, please) and in a second or two I might be
told "aragorn.stanford.edu" and maybe a few more to help jog my memory.
I even had an alias ("h") for the command as I have a poor memory and so
needed to use it often.

Nowadays I don't really know how to get the same effect without spending an
unconscionable amount of time in uninteresting conversation with one or more
nameservers.

Am I missing some zippy feature well-known to those who know it well?

-s

